com.okta.sdk.query

Interface DateExpressionFactory


  • public interface DateExpressionFactory
    An DateExpressionFactory creates a single condition (matches) for resource properties of Date type.
    Since:
    0.5.0

    • Method Detail

      • matches

        Criterion matches(String value)
        Convenience method that returns a new equals expression as a String expression, indicating the specified value should match the property value. Multiple values are allowed, for example: 
         account.createdAt().matches("[,2014-04-05T12:00:00]"): matches all Accounts created between the beginning of time and noon of 2014/04/05
 account.createdAt().matches("[2015-01-01, 2015-02-01)"): matches all Accounts created/modified between 2015/01/01 and 2015/02/01, excluding those created on 2015/02/01
 account.createdAt().matches("[2015-02-01T12:00:00,]"): matches all Accounts created between noon of 2015-02-01 and now
 account.modifiedAt().matches("2015-01"): is equivalent to "[2015-01-01T00:00:00.000Z,2015-02-01T00:00:00.000Z)" and matches all Accounts modified during January 2015
 account.modifiedAt().matches("2015-01-03T11:23:14.233"): matches all Accounts modified only at that exact instant represented by the ISO-8601 Timestamp
        Parameters:
        value - the value that should equal the property value (ignoring case).
        Returns:
        a new case-insensitive equals expression reflecting the property name and the specified value.

      • gt

        Criterion gt(Date date)
        Returns a new expression indicating the property value must be greater than the specified date. For example: 
         application.createdAt().gt(new SimpleDateFormat("yyyy-MM-dd'T'HH:mm:ss").parse("2014-01-01T12:00:00")): matches only those Applications created after 2014/01/01 at noon
        Parameters:
        date - the Date to compare the property value
        Returns:
        a new case-insensitive expression reflecting the property name and the specified value.

      • gte

        Criterion gte(Date date)
        Returns a new expression indicating the property value must be greater than or equal to the specified date. For example: 
         application.createdAt().gt(new SimpleDateFormat("yyyy-MM-dd'T'HH:mm:ss").parse("2014-01-01T12:00:00")): matches those applications created after or exactly at noon of 2014/01/01
        Parameters:
        date - the Date to compare the property value
        Returns:
        a new case-insensitive expression reflecting the property name and the specified value.

      • lt

        Criterion lt(Date date)
        Returns a new expression indicating the property value must be less than the specified date. For example: 
         application.createdAt().lt(new Date()): matches only those applications created before the instant specified by  new Date()
        Parameters:
        date - the Date to compare the property value
        Returns:
        a new case-insensitive expression reflecting the property name and the specified value.

      • lte

        Criterion lte(Date date)
        Returns a new expression indicating the specified date must be greater than or equal to the property value. For example: 
         application.createdAt().gte(new Date()): matches those applications created before or at the exact instant specified by  new Date()
        Parameters:
        date - the Date to compare the property value
        Returns:
        a new case-insensitive expression reflecting the property name and the specified value.

      • equals

        Criterion equals(Date date)
        Returns a new expression indicating the specified date must be equal to the property value. For example: 
         application.createdAt().gte(new Date()): matches only those applications created at the exact instant specified by  new Date()
        Parameters:
        date - the Date to compare the property value
        Returns:
        a new case-insensitive expression reflecting the property name and the specified value.

      • in

        Criterion in(Date begin,
             Date end)
        Returns a new expression indicating the property value must belong to the range specified by the begin and end dates Using "in" is equivalent to gte(begin).lt(end) where begin time is inclusive and end time is exclusive. For example: 
         application.modifiedAt().in(new SimpleDateFormat("yyyy-MM-dd'T'HH:mm:ss").parse("2014-01-01T12:00:00"), new Date()) matches those applications modified after or exactly at the noon of 2014/01/01 and before the exact instant represented by  new Date()
        Parameters:
        begin - the Date to use as the range start
        end - a Date to use as the range end
        Returns:
        a new case-insensitive expression reflecting the property name and the specified value.

      • in

        Criterion in(Date begin,
             Duration duration)
        This is a convenience method used to calculate the end timestamp for the range based on the begin date and the specified Duration
        Parameters:
        begin - the Date to use as the range start
        duration - the Duration used to calculate the end timestamp based on the value specified by begin
        Returns:
        a Criterion representing a given date range.
